property_search.html
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <title>Property Search</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="{{ url_for('static', filename='css/styles.css') }}">
</head>
<body>
<div id="search-page">
    <h1>Property Search</h1>
    <form method="get" action="{{ url_for('property_search') }}" class="filters" id="search-filters">
        <label for="location-input">Location:</label>
        <input type="text" id="location-input" name="location" value="{{ location_input }}" placeholder="Enter location or city">
        <label for="price-range-min">Min Price:</label>
        <input type="number" id="price-range-min" name="price_min" min="0" value="{{ price_range_min }}">
        <label for="price-range-max">Max Price:</label>
        <input type="number" id="price-range-max" name="price_max" min="0" value="{{ price_range_max }}">
        <label for="property-type-filter">Property Type:</label>
        <select id="property-type-filter" name="property_type">
            <option value="">All</option>
            {% for ptype in property_types %}
                <option value="{{ ptype }}" {% if property_type_filter == ptype %}selected{% endif %}>{{ ptype }}</option>
            {% endfor %}
        </select>
        <button type="submit">Search</button>
    </form>
    <div id="properties-grid">
        {% if properties %}
            {% for property in properties %}
                <div class="property-card">
                    <h3>{{ property.address }}</h3>
                    <div class="property-info">
                        Location: {{ property.location }}<br>
                        Price: ${{ "{:,}".format(property.price) }}<br>
                        Beds: {{ property.bedrooms }} | Baths: {{ property.bathrooms }}
                    </div>
                    <form action="{{ url_for('property_details', property_id=property.property_id) }}" method="get" style="margin-top: 5px;">
                        <button type="submit" id="view-property-button-{{ property.property_id }}">View Details</button>
                    </form>
                </div>
            {% endfor %}
        {% else %}
            <p>No properties found matching your criteria.</p>
        {% endif %}
    </div>
    <div id="back-to-dashboard-container">
        <form action="{{ url_for('back_to_dashboard') }}" method="get">
            <button type="submit" id="back-to-dashboard">Back to Dashboard</button>
        </form>
    </div>
</div>
</body>
</html>
```

"
Comments on Codes:
"The highest priority comment is about regulation #2 and #4: The backend code must have a route for the root URL '/' that serves the Dashboard page, and all frontend URLs must correspond exactly to backend routes.

**Review:**

- The backend code defines the route `@app.route('/')` for the dashboard page, which complies with regulation #2.
- The dashboard.html uses `url_for` to generate URLs for navigation buttons and property detail views, which aligns with regulation #3 and #4.
- Other pages like property_search, property_details, my_inquiries, my_favorites, agents, locations, property_inquiry, and back_to_dashboard all have corresponding routes in the backend.
- The frontend forms and buttons use `url_for` with the correct endpoint names matching backend route functions.
- The route `/back_to_dashboard` exists and is used for the "Back to Dashboard" buttons.

**However, there is one critical issue:**

In the route `/view_location/<location_id>`, the backend filters properties by `p['location'] == location_id`. But in the data, `location` in properties.txt is a location name (e.g., "Downtown"), while `location_id` is a numeric ID (e.g., "1") from locations.txt. This mismatch will cause no properties to be found when viewing a location by ID.

**This causes a broken feature and violates regulation #4 (routes correspond correctly to frontend code and data).**

---

### Suggestion to fix:

Modify the `/view_location/<location_id>` route to:

1. Read locations data and find the location name corresponding to the given `location_id`.
2. Filter properties by matching the `location` field to that location name (not the numeric ID).
3. Pass the correct location name as the filter to the property_search template.

**Example fix snippet:**

```python
@app.route('/view_location/<location_id>')
